#!/usr/bin/env python3
# claude-self-goal — let a running Claude Code session set its own native /goal.
#
# Claude Code's `/goal <condition>` makes the session keep working until a
# condition holds. Normally only a human can type it. This delivers that same
# line to the session *from inside the session's own Bash tool*, so an agent can
# set its own goal — including in background / non-tmux sessions.
#
# How the line is delivered (auto-selected by session type):
#   * inside tmux             -> `tmux send-keys` to our own pane   (no root)
#   * interactive pts session -> TIOCSTI the line into its pts      (needs root)
#   * daemon-managed session  -> `claude attach <id>` over its rv socket
#     (`/bg` sessions read input from a unix socket, not a pts, so TIOCSTI can't
#     reach them; the official attach client speaks that protocol for us)
#   * headless (`claude -p`)  -> refused (no way to deliver interactive input)
#
# Auto-discovery is fail-closed and classifies ONLY the nearest Claude Code
# ancestor (never a grandparent session): the pts path requires that pts to be
# the process's controlling terminal; the daemon path reads the id back from the
# process's own single listening rv socket. `--session <id>` is an explicit
# cross-session override that targets another daemon session by id.
#
# SECURITY: the tiocsti path uses TIOCSTI, a privileged keystroke-injection
# primitive the kernel restricts by default; the attach path uses the official
# client. Either way this is for automating YOUR OWN Claude Code sessions on a
# machine you control. See SECURITY.md. Do not run it on shared / multi-user
# hosts or against sessions you do not own.
#
